description: From Middle English ungrene, from Old English ungrēne (“not green”), from Proto-West Germanic *ungrōnī (“not green”), equivalent to un- +‎ green. Compare West Frisian ûngrien (“ungreen”), Dutch ongroen (“ungreen”), German ungrün (“not green”), Danish ugrøn (“ungreen”), Swedish ogrön (“ungreen”), Icelandic ógræn (“ungreen”).

entries.meaning: Having little or no vegetation or plant matter.
Environmentally unfriendly; harmful to or inconsiderate of the environment.

verbs.description: ungreen (third-person singular simple present ungreens, present participle ungreening, simple past and past participle ungreened)

entries.meaning: (dyeing) To expose to air after dyeing in indigo so that the greenish color fades away.
To make or become familiar with and adept in handling a new environment.
To change from green to some other color, as occurs with leaves in the autumn.
To urbanize or become less environmentally friendly.
